post_text: The Dublin Chamber has partnered with Dublin Bridges and Dublin City Schools to help those in our community who need it most. During the month of July, we are asking you to help by donating personal hygiene items such as deodorant, soap, body wash, shampoo, toothbrushes, toothpaste, feminine hygiene products, combs and brushes. Items can be dropped off on the front porch of the Dublin Chamber of Commerce, located at 129 S. High St. in Historic Dublin. Chamber staff will bring the items in the building each day. If you have any questions, please call 614-889-2001. More details can be found here: https://bit.ly/2UOHvlv

post_text: The Dublin Chamber has partnered with Dublin Bridges and Dublin City Schools to help those in our community who need it most. During the month of July, we are asking you to help by donating personal hygiene items such as deodorant, soap, body wash, shampoo, toothbrushes, toothpaste, feminine hygiene products, combs and brushes. Items can be dropped off on the front porch of the Dublin Chamber of Commerce, located at 129 S. High St. in Historic Dublin. Chamber staff will bring the items in the building each day. If you have any questions, please call 614-889-2001. More details can be found here: https://bit.ly/2UOHvlv

post_text: Thank you to our partners at the City of Dublin for this tremendous video. We will never forget those who gave everything to ensure our freedom. https://www.facebook.com/dublinohio/videos/550976548943865/
shared_text:
City of Dublin, Ohio - Government
May 25 at 5:12 PM ·

While we were not able to gather as a community this Memorial Day, individuals and small groups found unique ways to honor our fallen heroes while social distancing. We thank the members of the American Legion, veterans, residents and students who helped make this day special. Please enjoy this Memorial Day video, which features a compilation of “Taps” played by band students from all three Dublin high schools.

post_text: Eight to Automate, a First LEGO League team made up of District students, is one of 20 semi-finalists selected from more than 100 countries competing for the FIRST Global Innovation Award. On June 24-27, the team will be virtually presenting its flat roof monitoring system that detects excess strain on the roof and then sends a warning message to building owners. For more information, check out the Automates website: https://bit.ly/2zbDGiq. For interested 4th – 8th grade students, please see the Dublin robotics boosters website to join/start a team for the 2020-2021 season https://bit.ly/2Aat1Vb. #theDublinDifference

post_text:
Attention students! Do you have a 3-D printer at home?
Dublin City Schools teacher Greg King and some of his engineering and robotics students have been partnering with local companies and other educational institutions to design and print protective masks via 3-D printing. You can follow their work at this link: https://bit.ly/3dGG4gB

Mr. King and his students have been able to print 20-25 masks per day and are now seeking more people who have a 3-D printer at home, and may be interested in assisting in this project. Please email him at king_greg@dublinschools.net if you can help!

post_text:
On Thursday, April 16, from 7-8 p.m., Trevor Packer, Senior Vice President of AP and Instruction, will be hosting a webinar for parents and guardians to share information about this year’s at-home AP Exams and how to help your student prepare. This webinar will go into detail about the online exams and format, how to prepare at home for them, and answer common questions parents and students may have.
If you are a parent of an AP student, you can register for the webinar here: https://globalmeet.webcasts.com/starthere.jsp?ei=1302024&tp_key=73070ccd21 and tune in live with your student(s) on 4/16. A recording of the webinar will be available via the registration link after the live event.

post_text:
Dublin City Schools teacher Greg King and some of his engineering and robotics students are hard at work on a project that will soon lead to the 3-D printing of protective masks.
Mr. King teaches Computer Science, Engineering, and Robotics at Emerald Campus and Dublin Coffman. He became involved in the project thanks to a member of Dublin Scioto’s first graduating class who is now a physician.
Mr. King is taking some of his students on an incredible journey from concept to design to production. You can follow their work to this point and the great things to come at this link. https://bit.ly/3dGG4gB

post_text:
Dublin City Schools teacher Greg King and some of his engineering and robotics students are hard at work on a project that will soon lead to the 3-D printing of protective masks.
Mr. King teaches Computer Science, Engineering, and Robotics at Emerald Campus and Dublin Coffman. He became involved in the project thanks to a member of Dublin Scioto’s first graduating class who is now a physician.
Mr. King is taking some of his students on an incredible journey from concept to design to production. You can follow their work to this point and the great things to come at this link. https://bit.ly/3dGG4gB

Dublin Alumni Association is in Dublin, Ohio.
March 30 at 4:13 PM · Dublin, OH ·

Dublin Alumni community! Please consider a donation to help our students and their families during this time of crisis. Welcome Warehouse helps families in the Dublin City School District who are temporarily in need. They are fundraising for the Emergency Household Assistance (EHA) program. Many families in our community need temporary assistance because of job loss, underemployment, a health crisis or other challenges. The Covid-19 virus just adds another layer for families who are already struggling to meet basic needs. text WELCOME to 243725

https://www.welcomewarehouse.org/donate/
